Why isn't the Fed doing its job?
STANFORD – The nomination of new members to the US Federal Reserve Board gives people in America – and the US Congress – the opportunity to think about the world's most important central bank and its future direction.
The obvious, first question to ask is how it was possible for the Fed to fail so badly in fulfilling its most important mandate – ensuring price stability.
The fact that the Fed was completely surprised by the current inflation indicates a fundamental failure.
Clearly, institutional self-examination is now warranted.
Yet while monetary policy generates headlines, the Fed has become increasingly significant as a financial regulator.
A further major question is whether it will use its immense power to advance climate or social policy.
The Fed could, for example, deny credit to companies in the fossil fuel sector, require banks to grant credit only to firms with certified net-zero emission plans, or steer credit towards desired alternatives.
Furthermore, it could decide to explicitly incorporate its regulatory activities in the name of equality or ethnic justice by instructing banks on where and to whom to lend, who to hire and who to fire, and so on.
Yet before we turn to the question of which direction the regulation of the Fed will take or should take, it is first necessary to clarify the serious failure of the Fed.
In the year 2008, the U.S. government made a consequential decision: financial institutions could still largely obtain money for risky investments through the sale of short-term, highly volatile debt instruments, but an army of new regulatory agencies would henceforth assess the riskiness of the institutions' assets.
The hope was that the regulatory authorities would no longer overlook large chunks of subprime mortgages in the banks' balance sheets.
Yet, over the following ten years of detailed regulation and regular scenario-based "stress tests," the regulatory army of the Fed never once questioned what would actually happen in the case of a pandemic.
When the pandemic actually hit in early 2020, the Fed discarded its "Never again" promises from 2008 and intervened to an even greater extent.
In March, it became evident that commercial banks were unable to act as intermediaries on the market for ordinary U.S. government bonds.
Therefore, the Fed supported the market.
Critics had long pointed out the problems with the Fed's liquidity rules. The corrections on the markets would have been simple, but obvious reforms were postponed indefinitely.
Later, there was a run on money market funds.
The Fed rescued the money market funds again.
Nothing is easier to fix than runs on the money market, but such runs never occurred.
The Fed also financed the issuance of new municipal bonds and supported corporate bond prices by essentially offering a guarantee under the motto "Whatever it takes."
In 2008, the Fed and the U.S. Treasury had resisted the idea of increasing the market price of all mortgages as part of the financial sector rescue package - the Troubled Assets Relief Program.
Yet in 2020, with the "Powell put" among other things, an explicit floor for corporate bond prices was introduced.
The predictable rebuttal to this criticism will be: So what?
Lockdowns due to Covid-19 could have certainly triggered a financial crisis.
The flood of rescue measures has worked so well that our problem today is inflation.
We don't need to worry about systemic risks, because the Fed and the U.S. Treasury will simply put out each new fire with another flood of money.
The problem, however, lies in the incentives these strategies have created.
Why go through the trouble of using cash reserves or balance sheet capacity to buy at falling prices, provide liquidity, or treat a "fire sale" as a "buying opportunity"?
The Fed will take over everything and pocket the profits anyway.
Why issue shares as a company when you can simply take out a loan, knowing that the state will support the debt or help the company out of trouble, as was the case with the airlines?
Why hesitate as an investor when it comes to buying dubious papers, when their value is guaranteed in bad times by another "whatever-it-takes" promise from the Fed?
No wonder that America is sinking into debt.
All assume that taxpayers will pick up the tab during the next downturn.
Student loans, government bonds, and mortgages are piling up and waiting for their turn in Uncle Sam's rescue operation.
Yet every new crisis requires even more extensive transfusions.
Bondholders will ultimately refuse to put more money into rescue operations, and people will not enjoy billions of newly printed money.
If the expected rescue packages do not materialize, we will wake up to a major fire – and the fire station will have been burned down.
In 2008, regulators and legislators at least recognized the moral hazard and were concerned that in good times investors would reap profits while in bad times taxpayers would bear the losses.
In 2020, one could only indulge in self-congratulation regarding the rescue operations.
Exactly the Fed, which in 2008 failed to see the risks of subprime mortgages just as little as the pandemic in 2020, and now wants to conduct stress tests with regard to "climate risks," will certainly overlook the next war, the next pandemic, the next state bankruptcy, or another disruptive event.
The regulators of the Fed do not even ask about the aforementioned events.
And although babble about "interconnections," "strategic interactions," "network effects," and "credit cycles" is produced, it has not been possible to define "systemic" risk at all, apart from it becoming a catch-all term that grants regulators sweeping powers.
Regulatory authorities will never be able to predict risks, accurately measure the assets of financial institutions, or ensure that massive debts can always be paid off.
We must reverse the fundamental premise of a financial system in which the state always stands behind mountains of debt in bad times. And we must do this before the fire department is put to the test.
A better regulation can bridge partisan divides.
The Left is right when it claims that the big banks are inefficient oligopolies that benefit only a few Americans.
However, it starts from the wrong cause.
An immense effort to comply with regulations presents a major obstacle to market entry.
The call for "more" regulation is meaningless.
Regulatory provisions are either wise or foolish, effective or ineffective, full of unwanted consequences or well-conceived.
We need better regulation.
We need more capital, not thousands of pages of regulations.
Capital provides a buffer against all shocks and requires no prophetic skills from the regulators.
The Fed scandalously halted companies in the area of Narrow Banking and payment service providers that could contribute to fulfilling the financial needs of many people in America.
Before committing to the salvation of the planet and the rectification of injustices, the Fed should be held accountable for how poorly it fulfills its fundamental task of protecting the financial system.
